      "ESSeqNum": 0,
      "FacilityID": 1000116206,
      "SummaryText": "ACCIDENTAL RELEASE PREVENTION AND EMERGENCY RESPONSE POLICIES\n\nAt Celanese's Clear Lake Plant we are committed to operating and maintaining all of our processes in a safe and responsible manner. We use a combination of accidental release prevention programs and Emergency Response planning programs to help ensure the safety of our employees and the public as well as protection of the environment. This document provides a brief overview of the comprehensive risk management activities that we have designed and implemented, including:\n- A description of our facility and use of substances regulated by EPA's RMP regulation\n- An overview of our Accidental Release Prevention Programs\n- A summary of the Offsite Consequence Analysis\n- A five-year accident history for accidental releases of chemicals regulated by EPA's RMP rule\n- An overview of our Emergency Response Program\n- An overview of planned improvements at the facility to help prevent accidental chemical releases from occurring and adversely affecting our employees, the public, and the environment.\n\nSTATIONARY SOURCE AND REGULATED SUBSTANCES\nOur facility produces mainly commodity organic chemicals using a variety of chemicals and processing operations. The major products manufactured at the facility are acetic acid, vinyl acetate, carbon monoxide, and methanol. In our processes, we use the following chemicals that EPA has identified as having the potential to cause significant offsite consequences in the event of a substantial accidental release:\n\nToxics\n-Vinyl Acetate, produced at a rate of 1250 million lbs/yr, is sold entirely in the merchant market where it is used in paints and adhesives. The material is stored on site in inerted atmospheric tanks. \n-Ammonia is used onsite as the catalyst in Selective Catalytic Reduction of NOx emissions. Ammonia is received via tank truck deliveries and is stored onsite in a storage tank with a capacity of approximately 61,000 lbs of ammonia when liquid full.\n\nFlammables\n-Acetald"
    },
    {
      "ESSeqNum": 1,
      "FacilityID": 1000116206,
      "SummaryText": "ehyde is a byproduct in the production of vinyl acetate. It is recovered and shipped to another company location to be used as a raw material. About 800,000 lbs are stored on site as a liquid in a pressurized sphere.\n- A flammable mixture (40,000 lb) is found to occur at the Vinyl Acetate.   This mixture contains ethylene, methane and ethane above the RMP threshold quantity. The estimate is based on mass balance using a correlation to correct actual densities and account for compressibility factors.  \n-Propylene is used in a closed refrigeration system which cools part of the carbon monoxide production process. Propylene is received from Propylene pipeline supply and stored in three liquid vessels. The system contains a maximum of 18,000 lbs of propylene, if liquid full. The system is currently idled in place. \n-Methane and Synthesis Gas (Flammable Mixture) are a feedstock and intermediate, respectively, of the Methanol production unit. Methane is received from Natural Gas pipeline supply, and Synthesis Gas is created in the Methanol Reformer. Neither Methane nor Synthesis Gas are stored onsite, however both flammable chemicals exceed the RMP threshold quantity based on the capacity of the process unit's vessels, towers, and associated piping that would contain one of these chemicals. \n\nOur accidental release prevention programs and our contingency planning efforts help us effectively manage the hazards that are posed to our employees, the public, and the environment by our use of these chemicals.\n\nOFFSITE CONSEQUENCE ANALYSIS\nToxics:\nThe worst-case scenario assumes that the vessel with the largest amount of Vinyl Acetate had a catastrophic failure resulting in a toxic release. The release duration was estimated at 27.3 minutes using  RMP*Comp\u0099 an EPA-sponsored software tool.  RMP*Comp was also used to calculate the distances of 25 miles to reach the 0.26 mg/l (ERPG-2) endpoint.  Meteorological conditions for worst-case scenarios are defined in 40 CFR \u00a768.22(b) as a"
