      "SummaryText": "tmospheric stability class F, wind speed of 1.5 meters per second (3.4 miles per hour).  No other toxic scenario from a covered process resulted in a greater distance to an endpoint nor covered different public receptors from the selected scenario.\n\nOne Alternative Case Scenario was included for each of the toxic substances held on site.  Meteorological conditions for these alternative case scenarios were atmospheric stability class D (stable atmosphere), wind speed of  3 meters per second (6.7 miles per hour) and 77F. \n-\tA release of Vinyl Acetate from a 2\u0094 hole on the bottom of a storage tank that resulted in a release.  RMP*Comp was used to calculate the distances of 0.6 miles to reach the 0.26 mg/l (ERPG-2) endpoint.  \n-\tA release of Ammonia from the storage tank that resulted in a gas release. RMP*Comp was used to calculate the distances of 0.5 miles to reach the 0.14 mg/l (ERPG-2) endpoint.  \n\nFlammables:\nThe worst-case scenario assumes that the vessel with the largest amount of flammable substance (Acetaldehyde) had a catastrophic failure resulting in a vapor cloud explosion. The release duration is 10 min.  RMP*Comp was used to calculate the distances to of 0.6 miles to 1psi overpressure endpoint.   Meteorological conditions for worst-case scenarios are atmospheric stability class F (stable atmosphere), wind speed of 1.5 meters per second (3.4 miles per hour)\n\nTwo Alternative Case Scenarios were included to represent flammable substances held on site. Meteorological conditions for these alternative case scenarios were atmospheric stability class D, wind speed of  3 meters per second (6.7 miles per hour) and 77F. \n-\tRelease of Acetaldehyde from the storage sphere due to a 2\u0094 hole that results in vapor cloud explosion (VCE). RMP*Comp was used to determine the distance of 0.04 miles to 1psi overpressure endpoint.\n-\tRelease of Propylene from the storage vessel due to a 2\u0094 hole that results in vapor cloud explosion (VCE). RMP*Comp was used to determine the distan"
    },
    {
      "ESSeqNum": 3,
      "FacilityID": 1000116206,
      "SummaryText": "ce of 0.2 miles to 1psi overpressure endpoint.\n\nGENERAL ACCIDENTAL RELEASE PREVENTION PROGRAM AND CHEMICAL-SPECIFIC\nPREVENTION STEPS\n\nOur facility complies with the OSHA Process Safety Management Rule, and has taken all the\nnecessary steps to comply with the accidental release prevention requirements set out under 40\nCFR part 68 of the EPA. We take a systematic, proactive approach to preventing accidental\nreleases of hazardous chemicals. Our management systems address each of the key features of\nsuccessful prevention programs including:\n- Process Safety Information\n- Process Hazard Analysis\n- Operating Procedures\n- Training\n- Mechanical integrity\n- Management of Change\n- Pre-startup Review\n- Compliance Audits\n- Incident Investigation\n- Employee Participation\n- Contractors\nCommon Work Practices are in place such as energy isolation, hot work permits, and conduct of\noperations.\nConduct of Operations includes:\n- defining standards for handover of equipment between operations and maintenance,\n- following Standard Operating Procedures,\n- recertifying operators,\n- defining standards for equipment labeling,\n- approving and making notifications before removing safety equipment in service, and\n- verifying equipment readiness by operations prior to placing in service.\nAs part of our prevention efforts, we have implemented the following chemical-specific prevention\nsteps:\n- limit the level to which a tank can be filled In the vinyl acetate process:\n- use of nitrogen blanketing in all storage tanks to avoid flammability.\n- use of mounted water spray around the acetaldehyde sphere to prevent formation of a vapor cloud in case of a release.\nThese individual elements of our prevention program work together to prevent accidental chemical releases. Our company and our employees are committed to the standard that these management systems set for the way we do business, and we have specific accountabilities and controls to ensure that we are meeting the requirements of the law and our"
    },
    {
      "ESSeqNum": 4,
      "FacilityID": 1000116206,
      "SummaryText": "own internal standards for accident prevention.\n\nFIVE-YEAR ACCIDENT HISTORY\nWe keep records for all significant accidental chemical releases that occur at our facility. During the past five years there has not been a release involving materials covered under EPA's RMP rule that resulted in deaths, injuries, or significant property damage on site, or offsite injuries, evacuations, sheltering in place, property damage or environmental damage.\n\nEMERGENCY RESPONSE PROGRAM\nCelanese Clear Lake Site maintains an integrated contingency plan, which consolidates all of the various federal, state, and local regulatory requirements for emergency response planning. Our program provides the essential planning and training for effectively protecting workers, the public, and the environment during emergency situations. We are a member of CIMA (Channel Industries Mutual Aid), a consortium of area companies that coordinates and help each other during emergencies in which the individual plant's resources may not be sufficient to effectively handle the response.  \n\nCelanese  Emergency Response Plan (ERP) includes procedures for notifying facility personnel, including emergency response personnel, Local Emergency Planning Committee (LEPC) and the Pasadena Fire Department. The ERP defines the steps to deal with accidental releases of regulated substances to protect personnel, public safety, and the environment. The Plan includes actions to be taken including adequate first aid and medical treatment, evacuations, notification of local emergency response agencies and the general public.   In addition, there are emergency response field exercises performed annually where there are simulated accidental release of a regulated substances to ensure personnel and the emergency response team is prepared to respond accordingly.\n\nThe latest update to the ERP was made in 03/23/2020.\n\nPLANNED CHANGES TO IMPROVE SAFETY\nAs a result of the PHAs (Process Hazards Analyses) that are conducted periodically"
    },
